From aeb69b84422888b24efe79e51077a132da4941a5 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: cwintlhk <howardcheng@courtwell.com.hk>
Date: Mon, 8 Jun 2026 11:11:12 +0200
Subject: [PATCH 02/14] sourcing_reference: per-supplier letter allocation in
 RFQ ID (19.0.1.2.0)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Switches supplier-side RFQ IDs from RQ-{Prov}-{Seg}-{YY}-{NNN}
(pool-wide year-stamped sequence) to RQ-{Prov}-{Seg}-{Letter}-{NNN}
where Letter is the supplier's permanent index within the pool
(A, B, ..., Z, AA, ...) and NNN is the per-supplier RFQ count in
that pool. Two manufacturers in the same Province / Segment are now
distinguishable from the ID alone, fixing a real ambiguity flagged
by merchandisers.

  * New model sourcing.supplier.pool.member — one row per
    (Province, Segment, Supplier) with permanent Letter + per-supplier
    count. Concurrency-safe via SELECT ... FOR UPDATE on pool + member.
  * Extends sourcing.supplier.sequence with next_letter_index for
    letter allocation; existing count retained as pool-wide tally.
  * purchase.order.opportunity_id — Many2one to crm.lead so RFQs link
    directly to the originating opportunity (not via SO indirection).
  * Smart button on CRM Opportunity form opens linked RFQs/POs and
    pre-fills default_opportunity_id and default_gpc_segment_id on
    new records — merchandiser no longer types the opportunity link.
  * button_confirm flips RQ- to PO- prefix unconditionally after
    generation, so a draft RFQ that fills its segment late still ends
    up as PO- on confirmation.
  * Legacy IDs preserved. Migration sets next_letter_index = 0 on
    existing pool rows; opportunity_id starts NULL on legacy POs.
  * 15 tests covering letter allocation, pool isolation, opportunity
    inheritance, button_confirm end-to-end, and letter-encoding edges.
  * docs/RFQ_ID_GUIDE.md — one-pager for merchandiser handoff.
